In an interview with the German Netzwerk Junge Linke, the UKPA headship highlighted the similarities and dissimilarities of the two countries’ abortion laws and highlighted how focusing on bullying, it undermines and alienates heterosexual men like it alienates same-sex attracted men in the adoption arena. Regarding British and Polish abortion law, Baker stated:

“These laws are very dissimilar. The UK’s abortion law is a fragmented patchwork. It defines the ‘wrongful death’ of a baby but does not recognise it as an unborn person. The same applies to defending a woman’s right to choose abortion; while lower courts recently established that a doctor should give priority to the life of a baby born alive in an attempted abortion, this is not yet actually guaranteed, and parents do have the right to consent that the doctor switches off medical support for their baby. British law does not allow abortion for sex-selective reasons or for anencephaly, nor has there ever been a referendum on the matter. However there are examples of abortion for sex selection violations being criminalised, and a potential case for prosecution for sex-selective abortion.”
